A {{Nihongo|'''''suzu'''''|鈴}} is a ball-shaped [[Shinto]] religious bell. ''Suzu'' is a homophone meaning both "cool and refreshing." Ringing a handheld clustered ''suzu'' like [[Jingle bell|sleigh bells for musical instrument]], is the same as waving a {{Nihongo|''[[gohei]]''|御幣}}. It means calling gods and divinized heroes. Because it calls them, the bell gets their spiritual power. Through its use, people thus acquire authority and power, and evil is repelled. 

The ''suzu'' itself came to be believed to have spiritual power, so a small one became a bell charm called {{Nihongo|[[omamori]]|お守り}}, on sale at Shinto shrines.

There exists also another type of bell used in shrines, flat and without a clapper, which is rung using a mallet and is called {{Nihongo|waniguchi|鰐口}} (literally "crocodile mouth").

