A {{Nihongo|'''''suzu'''''|鈴}} is a spherical [[Shinto]] religious bell. ''Suzu'' is a homophone meaning both "cool" and "refreshing". Shintoists ring handheld clustered ''suzu'' like [[Jingle bell|sleigh bells for musical instrument]]. It means calling gods and divinized heroes, and in so doing, the Suzu gains spiritual power. Through its use, people thus acquire authority and positive power, and evil is repelled. 

The ''Suzu'' itself came to be believed to have spiritual power, so a small one became a bell charm called {{Nihongo|[[omamori]]|お守り}}, which is offered at Shinto shrines.

'Suzu' is also an uncommon female name in Japan that means "Little Bell" or "Tin", representing spiritual power that is gained through the Shinto-related Suzu bell. 

