[[File:Japanese shrine Bell01.jpg|thumb|Suzu hanging under the eaves of a Shinto shrine]] 
A {{Nihongo|'''''Suzu'''''|鈴}} is a Japanese word that refers to a bell, particularly one that is round, hollow, and containing pellets that sound the bell when agitated, similar if not exactly equivalent to a [[Jingle bell|jingle bell]]. Suzu come in various sizes, ranging from tiny ones that can be found on mobile phone straps and good luck charms, to large ones that can be found at [[Shinto]] shrines.

== Role in Shinto ==
''Suzu'' of different sizes are used in [[Shinto]]. At shrines, large ''suzu'' are often found in front of shrines, as it is said that ringing them alerts the gods. Handheld clustered ''suzu'', like [[Jingle bell|jingle bells]], are often used in Shinto ceremonies. It it is said that ringing the bells calls gods, divinized heroes and spirits. It is said that by ringing suzu, people acquire authority and positive power, and evil is repelled. The ''suzu'' itself is believed to have spiritual power, and so small suzu bell charms called {{Nihongo|[[omamori]]|お守り}} are offered at Shinto shrines.

== Trivia ==
''Suzu'' is also an uncommon female name in Japan meaning "Little Bell" or "Tin", representing spiritual power that is gained through the Shinto-related ''Suzu'' bell. 


