{{Nihongo|'''''Suzu'''''|鈴}} is a round, hollow Japanese [[Shinto]] bell that contains pellets that sound when agitated. They are somewhat like a [[jingle bell]] in form, though the materials produce a coarse, rolling sound.  ''Suzu'' come in many sizes, ranging from tiny ones on good luck charms (called {{Nihongo|[[omamori]]|お守り}}) to large ones at shrine entrances.

== Role in Shinto ==
At [[Shinto]] shrines, large ''Suzu'' drape over entrances, as it is said that ringing them calls [[kami]], allowing one to acquire positive power and authority, while repelling evil. Handheld clustered ''Suzu'', similar to [[Jingle bell|jingle bells]], are used musically at [[Shinto]] ceremonies.

== Other references ==
''Suzu'' is also a female name in Japan meaning "Bell" or "Tin". The kanji for ''suzu'' is often used to form a compound name, such as the well-known surname ''[[Suzuki (disambiguation)|Suzuki]]'', meaning "bell and tree".


